1ï¸âƒ£ Docker

Docker is a containerization platform used to build, ship, and run applications.
It packages the application and its dependencies into a container.

2ï¸âƒ£ Container

A container is a lightweight, portable runtime environment.
It runs applications consistently across different systems.

3ï¸âƒ£ Docker Image

A Docker image is a read-only template used to create containers.
It contains application code, libraries, and dependencies.

4ï¸âƒ£ Dockerfile

A Dockerfile is a text file with instructions to build an image.
It defines how the image should be created step by step.

5ï¸âƒ£ Docker Engine

Docker Engine is the core service that runs Docker containers.
It includes the Docker daemon and CLI.

6ï¸âƒ£ Docker Hub

Docker Hub is a public image registry.
Users can pull ready-made images or push their own images.

7ï¸âƒ£ Volumes

Docker volumes are used for persistent data storage.
They allow data to survive even after a container is deleted.

8ï¸âƒ£ Docker Network

Docker networking enables communication between containers.
It supports bridge, host, and overlay networks.

9ï¸âƒ£ Docker Compose

Docker Compose is used to run multi-container applications.
It uses a YAML file to define services.

ğŸ”Ÿ Docker vs Virtual Machine

Docker containers share the host OS, making them lightweight.
Virtual machines include a full OS and are heavier.
